title: Fix 32bit Android java API crash
body:
**Description**: Fix 32bit Android java API crash

**Motivation and Context**
- We have an open issue #8095 that on 32bit Android, if the model has multiple inputs, ORT will crash
- This does not repro on 64bit system, only 32bit Android (emulator and device)
- This does not repro with native Android executable, such as onnx_test_runner, onnxruntime_perf_test, only on ORT java API
- This does not repro when the model has only 1 input
- The java representation of the pointer array to the input tensor data is jlong which is 64bit, and it is casted to 32bit OrtValue**, so if we have multiple inputs, we will hit nullptr deref because a jlong will be converted to 2 OrtValue* and one of them will be all 0s
- Fix this issue by convert the jlong to OrtValue* before we call ORT->run
- TODO, add multiple input test cases and CI pipelines for 32bit Android

title: Create a quantized EmbedLayerNorm for ORT.
body:
Reduces memory overhead from a quantized graph containing a EmbedLayerNormalization fused Op. All weights and initializers are converted to `uint8_t`. Runtime simply dequantizes on the fly during batched/threaded execution. This reduces memory consumption on transformer models with large word embeddings since the entire embedding is not expanded to float32 during every invoke. Additionally, the `uint8_t` operations are much faster (up to ~3x on my machine with a large word embedding and hidden size of 768).

NOTES:
- I considered outputting as `uint8` but this works well for now - potential for a future pass.
- I tried consolidating logic between `qembed_layer_norm.h/.cc` and `embed_layer_norm.h/.cc` but was running into too many issues with complicated template declarations (see all the commits on `kreeger/qembed_layer_norm`. Ideally, the guts of QEmbedLayerNorm are eventually fully quantized and the logic diverges more.

title: Chang how numpy version is handled.
body:
**Description**:

First, numpy has binary compatibility, which means "binaries compiled against a given version of NumPy will still run correctly with newer NumPy versions, but not with older versions." So, if an onnx runtime package was built with numpy version A, then at run time it requires numpy version >=A.  

In the past, we let A = "1.16.6". However, there are two exceptions:
1. Training packages require a newer version of numpy. We build the package with numpy 1.19.5, but onnxruntime claims it requires 'numpy>=1.16.6'. So it's wrong.  If a user really got a numpy version < 1.19, it could crash. At least NumPy can't guarantee it would work.
2. Numpy 1.16.6 doesn't have a prebuilt package for ARM devices(people need to build it from source). So our ARM python packaging pipeline uses a newer version of it. 

In this change, we read numpy version from the installed packages at build time, to avoid manually keeping the build time/runtime consistency.  Now you are free to choose any numpy version you want. 


**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

title: Refactor QDQ optimizers to enable future usage in minimal build
body:
### Changes
- Add new SelectorActionTransformer that splits node selection from node modification to allow just the modifications to be applied at runtime in a minimal build. 
  - This is the first step of a few to enable a QDQ model to be optimized at runtime in mobile scenarios. Initial changes involve replacing the existing QDQ optimizers and adding the transformer infrastructure. Next changes will enable usage in a minimal build/ORT format model, as well as adding NNAPI specific QDQ handling.
- Add generic and QDQ specific helpers for selection (Selectors) and modification (Actions). The modification must maintain the graph edges in a valid state as Graph::Resolve isn't available in a minimal build to fix any issues with edges.
- Replace existing QDQ optimizers with optimizer based on new approach.

### Structure
- Selector instances run the checks to determine if a set of nodes can be modified by the optimization. This set of nodes is represented by a NodesToOptimize instance, which has entries for the target node, the input nodes and output nodes. 
- Action instances apply the modification to this set of nodes. 
- NodesToOptimize can be serialized as NodeIndex values so that in a minimal build we can re-create the NodesToOptimize instance (if all nodes are still valid) and call the associated Action. 
  - This minimizes binary size as we don't need any of the selection logic, and most actions can be implemented using generic code to move edges and replace a node (optimizations are generally the fusion/replacement of one or more nodes, with the input/output edges moving to the new node). 
- A general purpose SelectorActionTransformer is provided with which Selector+Action pairs are registered using the operators and opsets that these should be run for. 
  - Note that a separate SelectorActionTransformer should be created/registered for each related set of optimizations, so usage is based on that group of related things being available and registered in one place. 
  - It is expected that we'll convert more higher level optimizations to this approach so that a general purpose ORT format model can be optimized in different ways (e.g. run the QDQ as well as NHWC optimizations) at runtime based on the current device capabilities. 

### Motivation and Context
Improve flexibility and performance of mobile models.

title: Decouple Forward and Backward of ATenOp
body:
Decouple forward and backward for ATenOp, so the ATenOp forward (for inference or node doesn't require grad) can run. The PR includes:
- Remove attribute for ATenOp, all arguments will be inputs of ATenOp node, those non-tensor arguments will be CPU inputs.
- Use op_name and overload_name to determin the ATen operator.
- Remove ATenOp config for ATenOp forward run. All inputs will be converted to DLPacks, torch extension will convert these DLPacks to ATen operator arugments according to the operator schema and run.
- Remove ATenOpGrad. Use ATenOp node for both forward and backward.
- Move ATenOp's gradient definition to frontend. Use Python code to define ATenOp's gradient, we can use multiple ONNX Ops and ATenOp nodes to define a single ATenOp's gradient. The definition will be passed to backend in JSON format when backend build the gradient graph for ATenOp nodes.
- Move PyTorch exporter overriding function to the same place as the ATenOp gradient definitions, and also use Python decorator to register them.
- Add support to torch.argmax for forward run only, which is required by one of the models we are investigating on for now. ORT currently doesn't have CUDA kernel for ArgMax for OpSet12 or larger, because we are using CUDNN for the implementation for ArgMax, but CUDNN cannot support the new attribute "select_last_index" added since OpSet 12.

Moving forward:
- This change can support inference for those graph contains ATenOp node generated by exporter. Currently all codes are under ENABLE_TRAINING, in the future to enable running for inference, we need to move ATenOp schema and kernel from orttraining folder to onnxruntime folder.

title: Create a common directory for quantization code and functionality.
body:
This change creates a new folder for shared quantization code in `onnxruntime/core/quantization`. Going forward, all quantized kernels and tests should reference this canonical set of functions for using and accelerating quantized operations. This first change introduces a global `quantization.h` file with utility functions to handle quantizing and dequantizing vectors and lists of values to `int8_t` and `uint8_t`.

All code in this new header matches the logic used in the python quantization toolkit. Keeping these two aligned will ensure that quantization tests in c++ and python should match the exact implementation.

Additionally, I'm introducing a new class to hold scale/zp values - `quantization::Params<T>`. This class should be used to ensure that kernel or tests do not use an unsupported quantized integer width.

title: [WIP] Make Inference/TrainingAgents accept torch tensors
body:
**Description**: This PR is an attempt to make the separation of responsibilities between Inference/TrainingManagers and Inference/TrainingAgents clearer.

In the proposed change, Inference/TrainingManagers are responsible for mapping the torch module parameters, buffers, inputs and outputs to onnx model initializers, inputs and outputs. However it does not perform any data type conversion.

On the other hand, Inference/TrainingAgents are responsible for converting data type between torch tensors and ORTValues.

This PR removes the possibility to pass a path to an onnx file when we construct Inference/TrainingAgents but I believe that is minor because it is easy to load the file first and then pass the model to the constructor. Other than that the PR should not change any behavior.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve? This change allows users to wrap arbitrary ONNX model in Inference/TrainingAgents. For example,
```python
import onnx
import torch
model = onnx.load_model("my_model.onnx")
device = torch.device("cpu")
agent = InferenceAgent(model, device)
inputs = [torch.randn(16, 784)]
outputs, run_info = agent.forward(*inputs)
```
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.
